  "prompt": "What is AspectJ?",
  "response": "AspectJ is an aspect-oriented programming (AOP) extension to the Java programming language. It allows developers to modularize cross-cutting concerns, which are aspects of a program that affect multiple modules or components. Here's a comprehensive overview of AspectJ:\n\n1. Key Characteristics:\n- Extension to Java\n- Provides a way to implement aspect-oriented programming\n- Allows separation of cross-cutting concerns\n- Supports compile-time and runtime weaving\n- Integrates seamlessly with existing Java code\n\n2. Main Concepts:\n\na. Aspect:\n- A module that encapsulates cross-cutting concerns\n- Contains advice and pointcuts\n- Can modify or enhance existing code without changing original source\n\n```java\naspect LoggingAspect {\n    // Aspect definition\n}\n```\n\nb. Pointcut:\n- Defines a set of join points where advice should be applied\n- Specifies where and when specific code should be executed\n\n```java\npointcut methodExecution():\n    execution(* com.example.*.*(..));\n```\n\nc. Advice:\n- Code that is executed at specific join points\n- Different types of advice:\n  - before(): Executes before method\n  - after(): Executes after method\n  - around(): Wraps and controls method execution\n\n```java\naspect LoggingAspect {\n    pointcut methodExecution():\n        execution(* com.example.service.*(..));\n\n    before(): methodExecution() {\n        System.out.println(\"Method called\");\n    }\n}\n```\n\n3. Weaving Types:\n- Compile-time weaving\n- Load-time weaving\n- Runtime weaving\n\n4. Example Use Cases:\n- Logging\n- Transaction management\n- Security checks\n- Performance monitoring\n- Error handling\n\n5. Sample AspectJ Implementation:\n\n```java\npublic aspect TransactionAspect {\n    // Pointcut for methods annotated with @Transactional\n    pointcut transactionalMethods():\n        execution(@Transactional * *(..));\n\n    // Before advice to start transaction\n    before(): transactionalMethods() {\n        beginTransaction();\n    }\n\n    // After returning advice to commit transaction\n    after() returning: transactionalMethods() {\n        commitTransaction();\n    }\n\n    // After throwing advice to rollback transaction\n    after() throwing: transactionalMethods() {\n        rollbackTransaction();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n6. Advantages:\n- Improved modularity\n- Easier maintenance\n- Reduced code duplication\n- Better separation of concerns\n- Enhanced code reusability\n\n7. Limitations:\n- Learning curve\n- Performance overhead\n- Complex debugging\n- Limited support in some IDEs\n\n8. Configuration Options:\n- Maven/Gradle plugin\n- Eclipse AspectJ Development Tools (AJDT)\n- Command-line weaving\n\n9. Comparison with Other AOP Frameworks:\n- Spring AOP: Proxy-based, runtime weaving\n- AspectJ: More powerful, compile-time and load-time weaving\n\n10. Integration:\n- Works with Java EE\n- Integrates with Spring Framework\n- Compatible with most Java build tools\n\nExample of Combining with Spring:\n```java\n@Aspect\n@Component\npublic class PerformanceMonitorAspect {\n    @Around(\"execution(* com.example.service.*.*(..))\")\n    public Object measureExecutionTime(ProceedingJoinPoint joinPoint) throws Throwable {\n        long start = System.currentTimeMillis();\n        Object proceed = joinPoint.proceed();\n        long executionTime = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;\n        \n        System.out.println(joinPoint.getSignature() + \" executed in \" + executionTime + \"ms\");\n        return proceed;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nRecommended Usage:\n- Complex cross-cutting concerns\n- When fine-grained control is needed\n- Performance-critical applications\n- Large enterprise systems\n\nNot Recommended:\n- Simple projects\n- When overhead is a concern\n- When complexity outweighs benefits\n\nAspectJ provides powerful AOP capabilities, enabling developers to modularize and enhance existing code with minimal intrusion. However, it should be used judiciously and with a clear understanding of its implications.",
